{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491635"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1003"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1003"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0.06,0.75,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68015"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44865"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of a tertiary referral hospital with a 12 hour history of numbness between his thighs and an inability to pass urine. His recent medical history includes carcinoma of the prostate. His medication list includes goserelin. On examination he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination demonstrates an area of numbness in the inner thighs, extending into the perineum. Percussion of the abdomen shows an area of dullness extending three finger breadths above the pubis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain X-ray of the spine","Non-contrast CT spine","CT myelogram","MRI","PET scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe potential diagnosis in this patient is cauda equina syndrome and this must be confirmed or excluded promptly. Cauda equina syndrome is a serious complication of severe compression of the descending lumbar and sacral nerve roots. It generally presents with bilateral radicular pain, asymmetric motor weakness, hyporeflexia, and bladder dysfunction. This patient has sensory loss extending to the perineum and neurogenic bladder (evidence by dull percussion note above the pubis). If the diagnosis is confirmed, the patient will require emergency surgical intervention and decompression. An \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E is the diagnostic modality of choice for the diagnosis of cauda equina syndrome. An MRI can be used to define the possible changes of spinal epidural haematoma, disc protrusion, degenerative canal stenosis, and/or epidural abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain X-ray of the spine\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated when there is a suspicion of degenerative bone disease, fracture, or other bone pathologies. It is not a good diagnostic investigation to look for soft tissue pathologies or nerve compression pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast CT\u003C/strong\u003E spine is the next best alternative if MRI is unavailable or contraindicated. While it provides less detail of soft tissues and nerve roots compared to MRI, it can still demonstrate significant cord compression, bone metastases, and large disc protrusions. In rural or remote settings where MRI may not be immediately available, CT spine should be performed while arranging urgent transfer to a facility with MRI capabilities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT myelogram\u003C/strong\u003E is a more invasive test than MRI. It can identify nerve roots but MRI is preferred since an MRI can also rule out other possible differential diagnoses (eg, epidural abscess). A CT myelogram may be indicated if the patient has some contraindication to MRI (eg, electrical implanted devices).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EPET\u003C/strong\u003E scan shows the metabolic activity at a cellular level. It may be helpful for assessing metastases due to cancer. However, a PET scan is not useful for diagnosing radicular diseases (eg, cauda equina syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sudden onset of urinary retention and associated neurological symptoms must always raise the possibility of spinal cord compression.","MRI is the gold standard investigation for suspected cauda equina syndrome.","Non-contrast CT spine is an acceptable alternative if MRI is unavailable or contraindicated."],"references":["McNamee J, Flynn P, O\u0027Leary S, Love M, Kelly B. Imaging in cauda equina syndrome--a pictorial review. The Ulster Medical Journal; 2013;82(2):108. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3756868/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1003"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T19:06:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T19:07:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1003"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82951"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type